            <h2 id="what-a-newly-qualified-teacher-nqt-needs-to-learn">What a newly qualified teacher (NQT) needs to learn</h2>

            <p>There are 7 specific areas an NQT needs to learn and gain experience in.</p>

            <h3 id="using-the-curriculum">
              <span class="number">1. </span> Using the curriculum</h3>

              <p>The school’s curriculum sets out the knowledge, skills and values the pupils will learn. NQTs should use the school’s curriculum to help plan their lessons.&nbsp;</p>

              <h3 id="developing-subject-knowledge">
                <span class="number">2. </span> Developing subject knowledge</h3>

                <p>NQTs should know how to teach pupils the knowledge and skills they need to succeed for that subject. NQTs should use their subject knowledge to try to make the subject relevant to pupils.</p>

                <h3 id="building-pupils-confidence">
                  <span class="number">3. </span> Building pupils’ confidence</h3>

                  <p>Making sure pupils understand basic ideas before moving can help build pupils’ confidence. NQTs may need to explain the same ideas in different ways to help all pupils understand.</p>

                  <h3 id="predicting-areas-of-confusion">
                    <span class="number">4. </span> Predicting areas of confusion</h3>

                    <p>Understanding areas for confusion in a subject can help NQTs plan their lessons. Experienced colleagues can help NQTs identify these areas. NQTs may need to allow longer to go over these areas.</p>

                    <h3 id="developing-pupils-critical-thinking-skills">
                      <span class="number">5. </span> Developing pupils’ critical thinking skills</h3>

                      <p>NQTs can help develop pupils’ understanding of a subject. Getting pupils to think about the different parts of a problem and explore new ideas can help.</p>

                      <h3 id="creating-links-to-new-ideas">
                        <span class="number">6. </span> Creating links to new ideas</h3>

                        <p>Pupils learn new ideas by linking those ideas to existing knowledge. NQTs need to know how to explain how new ideas relate to what pupils already know about the subject.</p>

                        <h3 id="improving-pupils-literacy">
                          <span class="number">7. </span> Improving pupils’ literacy</h3>

                          <p>NQTs can improve pupils’ literacy by teaching reading, writing and language skills. This includes encouraging pupils to read and write outside the classroom. The curriculum explains the knowledge and skills NQTs need to teach pupils.</p>

                          <figure class="image embedded"><div class="img"><img src="https://assets.integration.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/image_data/file/89994/standard__7b.png" alt="women looking at laptop"></div></figure>

                          <h2 id="what-skills-an-nqt-needs-to-develop">What skills an NQT needs to develop</h2>

                          <h3 id="skills-which-help-plan-lessons">Skills which help plan lessons&nbsp;</h3>

                          <p>So NQTs can provide lessons that follow the curriculum, mentors need to help them:</p>

                          <ul>
                            <li>identify the main ideas, knowledge and skills for the subject</li>
                            <li>focus lessons on the main ideas within the subject</li>
                            <li>create activities, examples and demonstrations&nbsp;</li>
                          </ul>

                          <p>Mentors should also share any existing resources and materials the school has.</p>

                          <h3 id="skills-which-create-pupils-confidence-in-subjects">Skills which create pupils’ confidence in subjects&nbsp;</h3>

                          <p>An NQT needs to be able to:</p>

                          <ul>
                            <li>provide lessons that have a balance of explanation and practical activities to build skills and knowledge</li>
                            <li>use different activities to explain the main ideas over a period</li>
                            <li>explain how any new content relates to what they already know about the subject</li>
                            <li>set tasks that support pupils to learn the main ideas such as times tables quizzes</li>
                            <li>use a variety of examples and encourage pupils to challenge them</li>
                            <li>explain how problems are put together</li>
                          </ul>

                          <h3 id="skills-to-help-pupils-apply-knowledge-to-other-ideas">Skills to help pupils apply knowledge to other ideas</h3>

                          <p>An NQT needs to be able to:</p>

                          <ul>
                            <li>encourage pupils to think critically about a subject</li>
                            <li>get pupils to explore different ideas and think about the different parts of a problem</li>
                          </ul>

                          <h3 id="skills-to-help-develop-pupils-literacy">Skills to help develop pupils’ literacy</h3>

                          <p>An NQT needs to be able to:</p>

                          <ul>
                            <li>support pupils with different levels of reading and writing skills</li>
                            <li>explain the meanings of any unfamiliar words</li>
                            <li>encourage pupils to ask questions and summarise the text after reading it</li>
                            <li>promote reading outside the classroom</li>
                            <li>get pupils to respond to spoken questions in full sentences</li>
                            <li>teach pupils how to plan, draft and edit their writing</li>
                          </ul>
                        </div>
